---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { withBase } from '../lib/url';
---

<Base title="Colophon — Christopher Rangel" description="How this site was made">
	<div class="container">
		<section class="hero">
			<h1>Colophon</h1>
		</section>
		<div class="prose">
			<p>This site is built with Astro v6, deployed on GitHub Pages. Written by hand, no templates.</p>

			<h3>Type</h3>
			<p>
				Set in Lora throughout, for body copy and headings alike. Code, tags, and metric
				labels use the system monospace stack. The full scale lives on the
				<a href={withBase('design-system')} style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--ink);">design system page</a>,
				rendered as itself rather than redrawn as static images.
			</p>

			<h3>Photography</h3>
			<p>
				Shot on a Sony A6000 with a variety of lenses. I lean toward lower apertures outside
				of portraits. The kind of focus a plant needs is nothing like the kind a person
				needs. Edited in Lightroom, with occasional trips to Photoshop.
			</p>

			<h3>Built with</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Astro 6</li>
				<li>MDX for case study content</li>
				<li>astro-og-canvas for per-page Open Graph images</li>
				<li>GitHub Pages, deployed via GitHub Actions</li>
				<li>No analytics, no trackers</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>What I learned making this</h3>
			<p>
				Moving off Squarespace, I underestimated how much flexibility I'd get back.
				Hand-building the work page's geometric SVG patterns instead of reaching for stock
				thumbnails was the moment it really clicked: there's no platform ceiling here, just
				whatever I'm willing to build. Astro's content collections kept that flexibility from
				turning into chaos: one typed schema that every case study has to follow.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
</Base>
